.TH SIMPLE_SHELL 1 "April 2026" "Holberton School" "User Commands"

.SH NAME
simple_shell \- minimal UNIX command interpreter

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B simple_shell
is a simple UNIX command interpreter that reads commands from standard input,
parses them, and executes programs using system calls.

It is designed as an educational project to understand process creation,
program execution, and basic shell behavior.

The shell operates in both interactive and non-interactive modes.

.SH INVOCATION
When invoked, the shell reads commands from standard input.

If input is from a terminal, it runs in interactive mode and displays a prompt.
Otherwise, it executes commands non-interactively.

.SH OPERATION (CORE BEHAVIOR - MANDATORY PART 0.1 TO 1.0)
The shell performs the following steps in a loop:

.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Display a prompt (interactive mode only)
.IP \(bu 2
Read a line from standard input
.IP \(bu 2
Split the input into tokens (basic parsing)
.IP \(bu 2
Search for the command in PATH if needed
.IP \(bu 2
Create a child process using fork(2)
.IP \(bu 2
Execute the command using execve(2)
.IP \(bu 2
Wait for the child process using wait(2)
.RE

.SH COMMAND EXECUTION
Commands are executed using:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Absolute paths (/bin/ls)
.IP \(bu 2
Relative paths (./program)
.IP \(bu 2
PATH resolution (search in environment PATH)
.RE

If a slash (/) is present in the command, PATH is not used.

.SH BUILTIN COMMANDS (MANDATORY)
The following built-in commands are implemented:

.TP
.B exit
Exit the shell with an optional status code.

.TP
.B env
Print the current environment variables.

.SH ENVIRONMENT
The shell inherits the environment from the parent process.

The following variable is required:

.TP
.B PATH
Colon-separated list of directories used to locate executables.

.SH RETURN STATUS
The shell returns the status of the last executed command.

Standard values:

.RS
.IP 0
Success
.IP 126
Command found but not executable
.IP 127
Command not found
.RE

.SH ERRORS
Errors are printed to standard error.

Common errors:

.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Command not found
.IP \(bu 2
Permission denied
.IP \(bu 2
Execution failure
.RE

.SH SIGNALS
The shell handles:

.TP
.B SIGINT (Ctrl+C)
Does not terminate the shell; prints a new prompt.

.SH INPUT/OUTPUT
Input is read from standard input.
Output is written to standard output.
Errors are written to standard error.

.SH LIMITATIONS (BASE PROJECT - 0.1 TO 1.0)
The base implementation does NOT support:

.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Pipelines (|)
.IP \(bu 2
Redirections (>, <, >>)
.IP \(bu 2
Command chaining (&&, ||)
.IP \(bu 2
Quoting and escaping
.IP \(bu 2
Environment variable expansion ($HOME)
.IP \(bu 2
Job control
.RE

.SH ADVANCED FEATURES (SEPARATE TASKS)
The following features are implemented only in advanced stages of the project:

.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Command separators (;)
.IP \(bu 2
Logical operators (&&, ||)
.IP \(bu 2
Alias management
.IP \(bu 2
Environment variable handling (setenv, unsetenv)
.IP \(bu 2
Built-in cd command
.IP \(bu 2
Comments (#)
.IP \(bu 2
Command history
.IP \(bu 2
File input execution
.RE

.SH FILES
.TP
simple_shell.c
Main loop implementation

.TP
parser.c
Tokenization and parsing

.TP
executor.c
Command execution logic

.TP
path.c
PATH resolution

.TP
builtins.c
Built-in commands implementation

.SH EXAMPLES
Run interactively:
.RS
simple_shell
.RE

Non-interactive mode:
.RS
echo "ls -l" | ./simple_shell
.RE

